<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-07-29T17:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-07-29T17:45:00-05:00" n="741" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d741">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.516/169: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hanna</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-07-29T17:00:00-05:45">July 29, 1929—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 7:15 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>206. Your July 27, 2 p.m. I saw the President of Nicaragua. He states
                            that it has never been his intention to do more than indicate his desire
                            that the loan in question be made provided it could be made on sound
                            business principles. The President is not aware of a telegram from him
                            insisting upon the loan if it is unsound business. My talk with the
                            President leaves the matter to the judgment of those administering the
                            National Bank.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hanna</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
